    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c44fceb7-9448-437a-89c6-8c79705be5fc",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 10-year-old boy who appears his stated age, thin and energetic, often fidgeting in his chair and shifting his gaze around the room. He is casually dressed in school clothes that are slightly rumpled, with untied shoelaces and a backpack stuffed with crumpled worksheets and half-finished homework. During conversation he is friendly and talkative, but frequently interrupts, answers before questions are completed, and needs repeated redirection to stay on topic. His parents describe him as bright, curious, and affectionate, but constantly “on the go,” with noticeable difficulty sitting still during meals, class, or homework time.\n\nAt school, {patientName} struggles most with sustained attention, organization, and impulse control. His teacher reports that he often leaves his seat, forgets instructions, loses pencils and assignments, and makes careless mistakes despite understanding the material. He enjoys science projects, building toys, and outdoor games, but becomes frustrated with tasks requiring prolonged focus such as reading comprehension, handwriting, and multi-step math assignments. He has several friends and is socially outgoing, though he can be intrusive in conversations and occasionally gets into minor conflicts because he acts before thinking.\n\nAt home, {patientName} lives with both parents and a younger sister in a busy suburban household. He likes soccer, video games, riding his bike, and collecting trading cards. His sleep routine is inconsistent because he resists bedtime and often needs multiple reminders to settle down, though he generally sleeps through the night once asleep. Meals are regular but he is a somewhat picky eater, preferring snack foods and quick meals over sitting through long family dinners. Screen time tends to worsen restlessness if not structured, while physical activity noticeably improves his mood and behavior.\n\nHis family is supportive and actively engaged with the school, having sought evaluation after several years of escalating concerns about classroom performance, emotional frustration, and disruptive behavior. They describe no evidence of cruelty, substance exposure, psychosis, or major mood symptoms, but they do note frequent forgetfulness, losing belongings, and poor follow-through with chores. {patientName} is aware that he gets in trouble more often than peers and sometimes says he is “trying but can’t slow down.” Despite these challenges, he has strong verbal skills, a vivid imagination, and a warm relationship with close family members."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:0da18bdd-51bf-48b2-bb2c-7007a5155298",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was born at term after an uncomplicated pregnancy and delivery, with normal early motor and language milestones. His parents began noticing high activity level and impulsive behavior in preschool, but symptoms became more impairing in primary school when academic tasks required longer attention and better self-regulation. There is no history of seizures, traumatic brain injury, chronic medical illness, or developmental regression. He has never been psychiatrically hospitalized and has not had prior emergency visits for self-harm, aggression, or substance exposure.\n\nPast medical history is notable for mild intermittent allergic rhinitis and occasional constipation related to limited fiber intake. He has not previously taken psychotropic medication. Vision and hearing screening at school were reportedly normal within the last year. His immunizations are up to date. There is no known history of obstructive sleep apnea, but bedtime resistance and irregular sleep hygiene may worsen daytime behavior.\n\nLifestyle factors include high daily physical activity, participation in youth soccer twice weekly, and frequent recreational screen use after school. His diet is somewhat selective, with preference for processed carbohydrates and variable breakfast intake. Family reports that structured routines, short task intervals, and positive reinforcement improve behavior, while overstimulating environments and unstructured afternoons lead to more conflict. He currently has a school-based evaluation in progress for classroom accommodations due to attention problems and incomplete work."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
